inguish themselves from Europeans, for middle-class authors to assert their class privileges, for men to claim superiority over women in the kitchen, and for lesbian authors to insert themselves into the heteronormative economy of culinary culture. A Taste of Power engages in close reading of a wide variety of sources and genres to uncover the intersections of food, politics, and privilege in American culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCookbooksxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCooking, AmericanxHistory. 0aFood habitszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFoodxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a19th century food.  aamerican cooking.  aamerican cuisine.  aamerican culture.  aamerican studies.  acooking.  aculinary culture.  aculinary discourse.  aculinary literature.  aculinary texts.  aculinary.  acultural identities.  afood and agriculture.  afood and class.  afood and culture.  afood and gender.  afood and identity.  afood and power.  afood history.  afood lovers.  afood studies.  afood traditions.  afood writing.  afood.  ahistorian.  ahistory of cooking.  ahistory of food in america.  ahumanities.  apolitics of food.  aqueering cooking.  aqueering food.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028497540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096060240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520960602423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520960602/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY